{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488493"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.66,0.15,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44034"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29015"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44034"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a six-month history of a painless lesion on left hand. It began as a dry, erythematous patch that eventually became ulcerated and has not healed despite frequent emollient use. She has a medical history of a number of non-pigmented skin lesions, including actinic keratoses, that were managed medically.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Actinic keratosis","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Amelanotic melanoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe picture shows a plaque-like lesion on the hand with ulceration, associated with numerous surrounding keratoses. Sometimes on appearance alone, it can be very difficult to distinguish between a \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003E(SCC) and an ulcerated basal cell carcinoma. However in this case, with the background of actinic keratoses, this is most consistent with squamous cell carcinoma, where actinic keratoses are precursors to SCC. This is one of the most common skin cancers, typically occurring in sun-exposed areas. It is most commonly induced by prolonged UV exposure in those with Fitzpatrick skin types I and II.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActinic keratoses\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as solar keratoses, are pre-malignant lesions with the potential for malignant transformation to SCC if left untreated. The lesion pictured can be differentiated from an actinic keratosis due to the ulceration, which is suggestive of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinomas\u003C/strong\u003E (BCCs) share many common risk factors with SCCs. Classic features on examination include a pearly appearance with associated telangiectasia. In practice, biopsy Is often required to differentiate the two lesion types.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike the aforementioned lesions, \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoacanthoma \u003C/strong\u003Eare dome-shaped lesions originating from the pilosebaceous glands. They are a reasonable differential for SCC, as the central keratin plug may be mistaken as ulceration. Unlike SCCs, keratoacanthoma are raised and markedly symmetrical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmelanotic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E should always be considered as a differential for non-pigmented skin lesions. Biopsy will be required to exclude this differential, however SCC remains statistically most likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ulcerated skin lesions should raise suspicion of malignancy."],"references":["Arasu A, Meah N, Sinclair R. Skin checks in primary care. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2019;48(9):614-619. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/skin-checks-in-primary-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16841"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16841"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7cb6ad63-5ce0-4713-9f73-40a66b418b3d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7cb6ad63-5ce0-4713-9f73-40a66b418b3d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":396}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-05T16:44:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-05T16:44:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nul